[normal]&#xa0;[bold]Responses to specific questions from the Committee[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]Q1) What should the BBC be for and what should be the purpose of public service broadcasting? [bold]&#xa0;
[normal]18.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]In the UK
[normal],
[normal] there is strong and long-standing consensus in favour of public service broadcasting as a means of 
[normal]promoting social
[normal] 
[normal]and cultural 
[normal]goals
[normal] that go beyond 
[normal]correcting ‘market failures’
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]These goals
[normal] include: reflecting and shaping the nation’s culture and value
[normal]s through a breadth of UK-originated content; securing plurality of high-quality new
[normal]s
[normal] and information to help the public engage in the democratic process; and ensuring that content is universally available, easy to find, and free at the point of use
[normal]. In o
[normal]ur view
[normal], PSB 
[normal]also complement
[normal]s
[normal] and underpin
[normal]s
[normal] the editorial standards and risk-taking capacity of the rest of the market.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]19.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]The BBC is the cornerstone of 
[normal]the 
[normal]UK
[normal]’s
[normal] 
[normal]PSB 
[normal]system
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]Our mission is to inform, educate and entertain all audiences
[normal] with great programmes and services
[normal]. 
[normal]For us, serving the audience is an end in itself rather than 
[normal]a 
[normal]means to revenue maximisation.
[normal] The BBC’s contribution to British culture and society is captured in its Charter-defined public purposes.
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]20.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]In summary, the B
[normal]BC exists:
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]21.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]The success of the BBC is not an accident. Our mission and the economics 
[normal]behind this 
[normal]go hand in hand. Because the public share the cost of the BBC, each licence fee payer benefits from one another’s investment.
[normal] This means that there is universal access to better, cheaper programmes than would otherwise be the case. 
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]Q2) How well has the BBC performed in the current Charter period in achieving its mission and public purposes? Are the public purposes in the [bold]current Charter the right ones? How might they change?[bold] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]22.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]The BBC has a strong track record of delivery over the current Charter period.
[normal] 
[normal]We have modernised our service portfolio to keep pace with audience demands, 
[normal]launching the iPlayer and new HD channels. 
[normal]We have done this at a time when the BBC’s core funding
[normal] up to 2012
[normal] 
[normal](excluding 
[normal]the 
[normal]TV switchover allocation) broadly rose in line with inflation. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]23.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]Over the Charter period, t
[normal]he BBC’s reach has remained near-universal, with 
[normal]96% of UK adults using one or more
[normal] of our services each week
[normal].
[normal] The BBC is 
[normal]one of 
[normal]the most used public service
[normal]s
[normal] in the UK
[normal], being chosen by the public around 200
[normal] million
[normal] times every day
[normal]. 
[normal]BBC One and 
[normal]Radio 2 
[normal]are 
[normal]the 
[normal]UK TV and radio services with the highest figures; and BBC Online 
[normal]the only 
[normal]UK-owned website in the top ten most-used websites in the UK
[normal]. We also deliver a substantial 19
[normal] 
[normal]hours
[normal] of time-spent per user per week on average
[normal], factors which reflect the quality and diversity of our output and are crucial to our success in bringing the 
[normal]nation together.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]24.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]The BBC also excels on quality, with more UK viewers reporting that BBC One and BBC Two show well-made, h
[normal]igh-quality programmes than 
[normal]the other UK PSBs
[normal]. We outperform all international rivals too, with BBC One rated highest on quality out
[normal] of 66 major TV channels examined globally and BBC Two in third place
[normal]. 
[normal]This year, the BBC has received the highest number of nominations of any broadcaster in the world at the Golden Globes.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]25.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]Public trust in the BBC is crucial to our mission and an area 
[normal]where we strive to do better. Whilst the BBC’s rating is showing signs of recovery following Savile, and has been rising on a long term basis over the last decade, it is still someway short of pre-Savile levels
[normal]. However, 
[normal]as scores have been rising over th
[normal]e longer term, 
[normal]trust scores are still higher than 
[normal]in 
[normal]20
[normal]0
[normal]9
[normal]. The BBC is identified by
[normal] 
[normal]58% of the public as their most trusted source of news in the UK, by 
[normal]58% as the most accurate and by 49% as the most impartial – far ahead of the nearest alternative, 
[normal]ITV, 
[normal]on 14%, 13% and 14%
[normal]. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]26.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]The BBC has made substantial efficiency savings in
[normal] this Charter period 
[normal]and now costs only 4.3 pence per user-hour of content consumed
[normal], small in relation to the value of the
[normal] 
[normal]output 
[normal]produced. Similarly,
[normal] willingness to pay for the BBC is 
[normal]high
[normal].
[normal] We perform 
[normal]well by industry standards, costing only 40 pence per household 
[normal]compared, for example, with Sky’s average revenue per user of £1.53 per day.
