[normal]serve when asked to consider the good of society as a whole
[normal]. 
[normal]Research consisten
[normal]tly shows that the British public want a BBC that extends choice and brings them 
[normal]breadth, discovery, depth and enjoyment
[normal]. A ‘market failure’
[normal] BBC would not meet audience 
[normal]expectations or have the 
[normal]cultural 
[normal]impact that our mission requires.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]31.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]In addition, 
[normal]PSB is arguably at its most effective when it not only delivers high quality content 
[normal]but also 
[normal]encourages 
[normal]the market to do the same. 
[normal]Whilst it has occasionally been argued that 
[normal]the BBC 
[normal]crowds
[normal]-
[normal]out commercial investment, this misunderstands the 
[normal]significant impact 
[normal]that 
[normal]PSBs can have on 
[normal]audience expectations
[normal] of quality
[normal], 
[normal]creating
[normal] a 
[normal]‘
[normal]virtuous 
[normal]circle
[normal]’
[normal] of competition
[normal] 
[normal]between providers 
[normal]that
[normal] deliver
[normal]s
[normal] innovation and better programming f
[normal]or
[normal] all.
[normal] 
[normal]N
[normal]ations with well-funded PSBs investing in high-quality, diverse new content tend 
[normal]also 
[normal]to have revenue-strong commercial markets investing in these ways
[normal], 
[normal]a
[normal]nd the UK is a 
[normal]prime 
[normal]example of this. 
[normal]There is a strong argument that a ‘market failure’
[normal] BBC would cause 
[normal]the market to fail.
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]32.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]It is important to see the BBC’s scale in perspective. Over the last twenty years, the BBC has declined 
[normal]from c40% of all broadcas
[normal]t revenues to c25%, with the growth of pay-TV and advertising markets.
[normal] Moreover, audiences are benefiting as new companies offer them content and services which compete with traditional broadcasting. 
[normal] 
[normal]In turn, that means that the BBC is by no means the bi
[normal]ggest player in these converged markets, with a licence fee income of £3.6 billion compar
[normal]ed
[normal] to the revenues of companies such as BSkyB and BT at home (with revenues of £7.2 billion and £18 billion respectively in 2012/13), as well as 
[normal]highly-funded US rival
[normal]s such as Netflix, Lovefilm (owned by Amazon) and Google (£35.7 billion in 2012/13). 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]33.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]We believe the BBC’s scope should be to: provide linear and on-demand services (allowing creative and cost synergies between the two and providing for different usage pa
[normal]tterns); on a wide range of platforms and devices by IP and broadcast means (catering for offline groups and those, particularly the young, for whom IP delivery is the most natural approach); serve as publisher and broadcaster (integrating the best of in-h
[normal]ouse and third-party content in a single experi
[normal]ence). The BBC’s competitors operate
[normal] 
[normal]across the value chain 
[normal]and the BBC 
[normal]should be able to 
[normal]do 
[normal]so too in order to deliver 
[normal]its public mission
[normal] and serve audience
[normal]s
[normal] effectively
[normal]. 
