[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]B) What balance should be struck [bold]in what the BBC p[bold]r[bold]oduces in-house, commissions externally and leaves entirely to others to create?[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]34.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]The right balance in the BBC’s supply base between in-house and external production 
[normal]should 
[normal]be determined by audience and public interest objectives. 
[normal]The UK 
[normal]production sector is strong, second only to the US on 
[normal]overseas
[normal] content sales
[normal]. It is
[normal] based on a mixed 
[normal]and competitive 
[normal]e
[normal]cology
[normal] 
[normal]of
[normal] 
[normal]i
[normal]ndependent producers
[normal], 
[normal]in-house 
[normal]production arms (
[normal]e.g. 
[normal]BBC) and broadcaster-owned production arms supplying various parties (e.g.
[normal] ITV).
[normal] Each element brings a complementary set of strengths to the mix.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]35.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal] 
[normal]Our goal is to ensure the best programmes for audiences and the creation of IP that promotes British creativity abroad. We believe that a 
[normal]strong in-house production base is 
[normal]necessary
[normal] to meet these goals. 
[normal]BBC in-house production promotes a focus on quality and public service values; guarantees the cost-effective supply of a wide range of genres; 
[normal]creates
[normal] creative clusters across the UK
[normal]; 
[normal]and provides the BBC with vital IP, facilitating 
[normal]exports, the launch of new services like iPlayer and operation at scale o
[normal]verseas through BBC Worldwide
[normal]. 
[normal]UK licence fee payers effectively own the pool of BBC IP created through fully-owned works. 
[normal]Given the growing importance of IP in the media value chain,
[normal] a scale position is essential if we are to build strong global brands and deliver an economic return to the UK creative economy. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]36.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]The UK independent sector promotes competition
[normal], 
[normal]new ideas and content formats, and has seen revenues grow from £120m in 1982
[normal] to a substantial £2.3 billion in 2010
[normal] – 25% 
[normal]of this 
[normal]from overseas commissions and sales. 
[normal]The BBC benefits from a strong independent sector.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]37.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]The
[normal] Window of Creative Competition is effective in allowing the BBC to find the best ideas from in-house and 
[normal]independent
[normal] producers
[normal], and r
[normal]ights holders will 
[normal]also 
[normal]soon benefit from the permanent download-to-own window planned for BBC
[normal] commissioned
[normal] 
[normal]content. The BBC consistently meets its target of 25% external spend for 
[normal]BBC Online, and through its plans for iPlayer and Online to 2016/17 will likely increase this figure. 
