[normal]Q8) What comparisons can be made with the provision of public service content in other countries? [bold]&#xa0;
[normal]56.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]Internationally
[normal],
[normal] PSB is at a crossroads, with
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]some PSBs in rude health and successfully adapting their services and funding to a converged environment and others facing considerable difficulties. Furthermore, the overall trend is that where PSBs are well-funded and strong
[normal] – investing in original content, diverse schedules and quality and thereby driving ‘competition for quality’ – so too are commercial broadcasters.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] This is true, for example, in the UK, which has 
[normal]a 
[normal]particularly rich PSB and commercial ecosystem. It is in
[normal] stark contrast to countries
[normal], such as Portugal
[normal],
[normal] 
[normal]where PSB has faced major funding cuts and threats of privatisation, or Greece which witnessed the forcible closure of a PSB
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]Such challenges to PSB suggest there is a 
[normal]tipping-point
[normal] 
[normal]from which it is hard to r
[normal]ecover.
