[normal]Q9[bold]) How should the BBC be governed, regulated and held accountable beyond 2016? [bold]In a constantly evolving communications environment, does a 10-year Royal Charter and Agreement with the Secretary of State, together, provide the most appropriate constitutiona[bold]l framework for the BBC?[bold] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]58.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]The BBC’s governance model beyond 2016 will be considered as part of Charter Review and we do not wish to pre
[normal]-
[normal]judge that process. 
[normal]Our priority is to make the existing model work as effectively as possible, within the constraints 
[normal]of the current Charter. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]59.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]In September
[normal] 2013
[normal], 
[normal]the Trust and Executive 
[normal]announced 
[normal]a joint 
[normal]review 
[normal]of 
[normal]the BBC’s internal governance systems and structures, and the culture that surrounds them. We did this in response to a number of events that prompted legitimate questions about the effectiveness of the BBC’s system of governance, both within and between t
[normal]he Trust and Executive. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]60.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]The 
[normal]outcome of the 
[normal]review, announced on 11
[normal]th
[normal] December
[normal], is that the respective responsibilities of the Trust and Executive Board will be clarified, within the terms of the Charter. The Trust will focus on its oversight and regulat
[normal]ory role, ensuring we are answerable to licence fee payers.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] The Executive will be responsible for running the organisation. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]61.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]The role of the Executive Board will be strengthened.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] It will be responsible for all aspects of management and operations and th
[normal]e main decision-making forum for the 
[normal]BBC.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] The role and number of non-executive directors on the 
[normal]Executive Board 
[normal]will increase, starting with the appointment of Sir Howard Stringer, previously CEO and chairman of Sony, from January 2014. We will also reduc
[normal]e the number of pan-BBC boards by more than 60%. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]62.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]These changes are designe
[normal]d to deliver simpler 
[normal]structures, bet
[normal]ter decision-making and proper 
[normal]accountability.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] They 
[normal]should 
[normal]ensure everyone in
[normal]side and outside the BBC is 
[normal]clear about who is responsible for 
[normal]major decisions and projects. The BBC should also be able to make faster decisions and reduce the time senior managers spend in meetings and increase the time spent making output for audiences.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]63.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]As with governance, the most appropriate constitutional model 
[normal]for the BBC will be the
[normal] subject of debate at Charter review
[normal]. 
[normal]Our starting-point is that 
[normal]a Charter and Agreement model safeguard the BBC’s independence and provide stability for long-term investm
[normal]ent.
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]64.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]The Charter model underpins the BBC’s unique governance structure and funding model, explicitly committing the Government of the day to respect the editorial and operational independence of the BBC. Charter terms are subject to extensive political d
[normal]eba
[normal]te at the time of Charter review
[normal], ensuring appropriate parliamentary and public scrutiny, but 
[normal]with a 
[normal]relatively fixed period to provide room for the BBC to deliver on its commitments. The ten-year 
[normal]term gives the BBC a sufficient horizon over which to pl
[normal]an investment and helps to keep decisions on the BBC’s remit out-of-step with the electoral cycle. The Charter also has a symbolic value, we believe, emphasising for the UK public and stakeholders the special role and responsibilities which the BBC has as 
[normal]an independent broadcaster and trusted national institution.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]65.
[normal]&#xa0; 
[normal]Furthermore, the model 
[normal]fits with 
[normal]an evolving communications environment, 
[normal]providing flexibility for the BBC to develop in line with new technologies and audience tastes. 
